# Frontend CSS, Tailwind, and Accessibility Rules

## Styling & CSS

- **No inline styles**: Do not use `style={{ ... }}` in React components except for truly dynamic values that cannot be expressed with Tailwind (e.g. canvas coordinates). Prefer Tailwind utility classes and shared component primitives.
- **Tailwind-first**: Use Tailwind CSS for layout, spacing, color, and typography. Create small wrapper components (e.g. `Button`, `Card`, `Badge`) instead of repeating long class strings.
- **Design tokens**: Use Tailwind config for brand colors, spacing, and typography rather than hardcoded hex values in components.
- **Consistent layout**: Use responsive Tailwind utilities (`sm: md: lg:`) to maintain a good experience on laptops, tablets, and mobile.

## Accessibility (WCAG)

- **Color contrast**: All text and icon colors must meet WCAG AA contrast against their backgrounds. Use Tailwind `text-*` and `bg-*` that follow the design system; avoid custom low-contrast hex values.
- **Semantic HTML**: Prefer semantic elements (`button`, `nav`, `main`, `section`, `h1`–`h3`, `table` with `thead`/`tbody`) over generic `div`s, especially for navigation, headings, and tables.
- **Keyboard support**: All interactive elements must be reachable and operable with keyboard only. Never rely solely on `onClick` on non-interactive tags; use `button`, `a`, or add correct `role`, `tabIndex`, and key handlers.
- **ARIA & labels**: Provide accessible names (`aria-label`, `aria-labelledby`) for icons-only buttons and interactive controls where the visible label is not clear.

## Badges / Pills

- **Consistent dimensions**: All badge/pill components must use a shared `Badge` primitive with a fixed min-width so that all variants render with the same width (based on the widest expected label).
- **Centralized mapping**: Maintain a single configuration map for badge variants (e.g. `critical`, `important`, `nice`, `future`, `billed`, `pending`) that defines label, colors, and icon so those stay consistent across the app.
- **Text scale**: Use Tailwind text utilities for badges (`text-xs`, `font-semibold`, `tracking-wide`) instead of per-usage tweaks.

## React + Tailwind Libraries

- **Headless UI / Radix**: Prefer accessible primitives from `@headlessui/react` or `@radix-ui/react-*` for complex widgets (dialogs, menus, tabs) instead of hand-rolled versions.
- **Helpers**: Use `clsx` and `tailwind-merge` (or `cn` helper) to compose Tailwind class names instead of manual string concatenation.
- **Forms & inputs**: Use a small set of shared form components (e.g. `TextField`, `Slider`, `Toggle`) styled with Tailwind and built for accessibility.

## Build & Dependencies

- **Framework**: Use Next.js App Router with Tailwind CSS for the main web app.
- **Dependencies** (install once in the project):
  - Core: `next react react-dom`
  - Styling: `tailwindcss postcss autoprefixer`
  - UI helpers: `@headlessui/react @heroicons/react clsx tailwind-merge`
- **Build commands**:
  - `npm run dev` for local development
  - `npm run build` for production build
  - `npm run lint` to keep ESLint clean; fix accessibility and styling issues before merging.

